  "prompt": "What universities for MS in CS should be considered with GRE - 317/340, CGPA - 9.15/10 and TOEFL - 102?",
  "response": "With a GRE score of 317, a CGPA of 9.15/10, and a TOEFL score of 102, you have a competitive profile for many universities offering a Master\u2019s in Computer Science. Here\u2019s a list of universities you might consider, categorized by their general reputation and competitiveness:\n\n### Top-Tier Universities\n1. **University of California, Berkeley (UC Berkeley)**\n2. **Carnegie Mellon University**\n3. **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n4. **Stanford University**\n5. **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n\n### High-Quality Universities\n1. **University of Michigan, Ann Arbor**\n2. **University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign**\n3. **University of California, San Diego (UCSD)**\n4. **University of Washington**\n5. **Georgia Institute of Technology**\n\n### Good Universities with Strong CS Programs\n1. **University of California, Santa Barbara (UCSB)**\n2. **University of Texas at Austin**\n3. **University of Wisconsin-Madison**\n4. **University of Southern California (USC)**\n5. **University of Florida**\n\n### Considerations for Your Application\n- **Research Interests:** Make sure to align your research interests with those of the faculty at the universities you apply to.\n- **Letters of Recommendation:** Strong recommendations from professors or industry professionals can enhance your application.\n- **Personal Statement:** A well-crafted personal statement discussing your background, interests, and motivations for pursuing a master\u2019s can make a significant impact.\n- **Extracurricular Activities:** If you have relevant projects, internships, or involvement in tech clubs, be sure to highlight these in your application.\n\n### Final Thoughts\nIt's important to research each program's specific requirements, deadlines, and whether they are test-optional for the GRE. Many universities reevaluated GRE requirements during the pandemic, and some may continue to do so. Visit each university's website for the most current information and consider reaching out to current students or alumni for personal insights. Good luck!",
